02:24.545 --> 02:32.551
♪

03:29.209 --> 03:32.344
- Noah, is that you?

03:36.316 --> 03:37.883
Come on in for a second.

03:44.290 --> 03:47.793
Sit down.
Relax.

03:53.833 --> 03:58.337
So.
How's the writing coming?

03:58.339 --> 03:59.938
- It's fine.

03:59.940 --> 04:02.241
- It's a nice place to work,
isn't it?

04:02.243 --> 04:07.779
So quiet, so much peace.

04:07.781 --> 04:10.249
I noticed you out there
swimming.

04:10.251 --> 04:12.484
And it reminded me of something
I used to do when I wanted

04:12.486 --> 04:15.454
To avoid the page.

04:15.456 --> 04:19.324
I didn't swim,
but I'd go play tennis.

04:19.326 --> 04:22.594
Four hours a day.
I had a tennis partner,

04:22.596 --> 04:25.597
A little jewish fellow
named arnold.

04:25.599 --> 04:29.668
And I'd beat him roundly
every set.

04:29.670 --> 04:34.740
And I'd come home feeling
so good about myself.

04:34.742 --> 04:38.043
And too tired to write a word.

04:38.045 --> 04:40.946
Finally, margaret said to me,
"bruce, why don't you write

04:40.948 --> 04:44.650
Ten pages and then go play
tennis?"

04:44.652 --> 04:48.353
Well, I took her up on it.

04:48.355 --> 04:49.955
And the next time I saw arnold,

04:49.957 --> 04:51.757
It was a year later.

04:51.759 --> 04:55.060
He whooped my ass.

04:55.062 --> 04:57.829
But I had a <i>new york times</i>
<i> bestseller.</i>

05:08.041 --> 05:12.377
- Well, bruce, I'm gonna go
and--gonna get some clothes on.

05:12.379 --> 05:13.779
- Good.

05:17.784 --> 05:19.751
Noah?

05:22.555 --> 05:25.057
I'm glad we talked.

06:20.480 --> 06:22.914
- Don't wake up.

06:32.125 --> 06:35.794
- Good morning.

06:44.871 --> 06:49.508
What do you think of this one?

06:49.510 --> 06:54.780
- I like it.
- Better than...This one?

06:54.782 --> 06:57.149
- What's the difference?
- The first one's from kenya.

06:57.151 --> 07:00.185
This one's from brazil.

07:00.187 --> 07:02.821
And the kenyan one is made
by a woman's collective,

07:02.823 --> 07:05.624
And the proceeds go to
their daughters' education.

07:05.626 --> 07:09.761
But the brazilian one is made
from recycled cardboard pulp,

07:09.763 --> 07:13.031
Which is kind of amazing.

07:13.033 --> 07:14.099
- Price differential?

07:14.101 --> 07:15.967
- Negligible.

07:15.969 --> 07:18.970
Um, I have to skype this morning
with leslie,

07:18.972 --> 07:21.072
So we can do inventory.
Can you take the kids?

07:21.074 --> 07:23.041
- Well, I'm supposed to have
a breakfast meeting with harry.

07:23.043 --> 07:24.709
- Oh, good, he called you.

07:24.711 --> 07:26.077
- Actually, I called him.

07:26.079 --> 07:28.513
- I told him to call you.
- He didn't.

07:28.515 --> 07:31.183
- Whitney, can you watch trevor
and stacey for a couple hours?

07:31.185 --> 07:35.187
- I can't, grandma got me
an interview to be an au pair.

07:35.189 --> 07:37.956
- What?
- I'll call you right back.

07:37.958 --> 07:39.925
Yes, it's a woman on the board.

07:39.927 --> 07:41.793
Her grandchildren
are visiting from london,

07:41.795 --> 07:43.562
And it's just too much
for her to handle.

07:43.564 --> 07:44.663
- So you thought whitney could
handle it?

07:44.665 --> 07:46.198
- What's that supposed to mean?

07:46.200 --> 07:48.467
- Well, you realize this is
a real responsibility?

07:48.469 --> 07:51.236
You're gonna have to
go there every day

07:51.238 --> 07:53.205
And these people
will be relying on you.

07:53.207 --> 07:54.706
- Mom, can you not talk to me

07:54.708 --> 07:55.707
Like I'm some sort
of delinquent?

07:55.709 --> 07:57.542
- Honestly, helen?

07:57.544 --> 07:59.578
I thought you wanted her to have
something to do this summer

07:59.580 --> 08:03.682
So she didn't get into trouble
having s-e-x.

08:03.684 --> 08:06.585
- They can spell, mom.
They can all spell.

08:06.587 --> 08:08.220
- I'll reschedule the meeting
with harry.

08:08.222 --> 08:10.222
- No, don't, it's important.
I want you to go.

08:10.224 --> 08:14.059
Dad, you're on childcare
this morning.

08:24.570 --> 08:27.138
- Hi.
- Hi.

08:27.140 --> 08:29.140
Sorry I'm late.
There was a bit of chaos

08:29.142 --> 08:30.642
In the house this morning.

08:30.644 --> 08:32.110
- No, please.
It's not a problem.

08:32.112 --> 08:34.246
Four kids--how do you find
time to do anything?

08:34.248 --> 08:38.583
Never mind write.
- Yeah, I tend to get up early.

08:38.585 --> 08:42.153
- How early do you get up?
- Uh, 5:00, sometimes 4:00.

08:42.155 --> 08:43.922
Write for a few hours before
the kids get up.

08:43.924 --> 08:46.291
- Is that a little tip you
learned from your father-in-law?

08:46.293 --> 08:51.029
- Right, yeah, I guess--
I guess he does that too.

08:51.031 --> 08:53.298
Hey, can I get some coffee?

08:53.300 --> 08:56.067
So thanks for meeting with me.
- Oh, oh, no, it's my pleasure.

08:56.069 --> 08:59.538
I never get the chance to meet
serious young writers anymore.

08:59.540 --> 09:03.742
These days, it's all fantasy or
memoir or cheap detective shit.

09:03.744 --> 09:08.280
Or everyone is self publishing
online and wasting their talent.

09:08.282 --> 09:10.315
Every year I tell myself, you
know what, I'm gonna finally--

09:10.317 --> 09:11.950
I'm gonna get out of
this business

09:11.952 --> 09:15.654
And then, somehow, I don't.
God knows why.

09:15.656 --> 09:17.022
It's not the money.

09:17.024 --> 09:20.825
It might be inertia
or...Fear.

09:20.827 --> 09:22.193
My wife just went back
to get her master's

09:22.195 --> 09:25.297
And we got two kids
in private schools.

09:25.299 --> 09:27.632
I'm sorry, I have no idea why
I'm telling you this.

09:27.634 --> 09:31.770
- That's okay.
I-I'm interested.

09:31.772 --> 09:33.338
- You got an honest face.

09:33.340 --> 09:36.708
Anyone ever tell you that?

09:36.710 --> 09:40.045
- Uh, yeah.
I guess I heard it before.

09:40.047 --> 09:41.646
- Well, you know what?
We can save my life story

09:41.648 --> 09:43.181
For another time.

09:43.183 --> 09:45.350
Why don't you tell me about
this book of yours?

09:45.352 --> 09:48.920
- Well, uh...I'm not sure
there's much to tell yet.

09:48.922 --> 09:51.222
It's kinda why I wanted
to meet with you.

09:51.224 --> 09:53.191
- So you, okay, you said
it was set out here?

09:53.193 --> 09:58.063
- Right.
- So what is it about?

09:58.065 --> 10:03.935
- Well, I think it's about the
death of the american pastoral.

10:03.937 --> 10:08.340
How, uh, the authenticity
of a small tourist town

10:08.342 --> 10:10.075
Gets co-opted
and commercialized

10:10.077 --> 10:13.144
Until it becomes
a parody of itself.

10:14.280 --> 10:16.881
- And...?

10:16.883 --> 10:19.150
- Uh, that's all I got so far.

10:19.152 --> 10:20.852
- Are there any characters?

10:20.854 --> 10:23.688
- Sure, sure, yeah.
No, um...There's a--yeah.

10:23.690 --> 10:27.359
Small town girl, city guy.
They meet, fall in love.

10:27.361 --> 10:30.829
- But...?
- But he's already married.

10:30.831 --> 10:31.863
- And...?
- And so is she.

10:31.865 --> 10:33.632
- Oh.

10:36.702 --> 10:41.139
Well, I've read it before.
- Right.

10:41.141 --> 10:43.341
- So how is it different?

10:46.979 --> 10:49.748
- He kills her.

10:49.750 --> 10:52.117
In the end.

10:52.119 --> 10:55.253
- Okay.
Now I'm interested.

10:55.255 --> 10:57.389
How does he do it?

10:57.391 --> 10:59.391
- I don't know.

10:59.393 --> 11:01.292
- Why does he do it?

11:01.294 --> 11:03.895
- I don't know that either.

11:03.897 --> 11:07.265
- To save himself and protect
the life that he's got?

11:07.267 --> 11:09.401
- Right.

11:09.403 --> 11:13.071
- So this publishing house
that you're with.

11:13.073 --> 11:16.441
- Wind chime press.
- You sign a contract?

11:16.443 --> 11:18.176
- No, no.
Handshake deal.

11:18.178 --> 11:20.011
- Good.
Well, I tell you what.

11:20.013 --> 11:22.681
When you got some pages, I want
you to show them to me first.

11:22.683 --> 11:24.783
- Okay, great.
I'll do that.

11:24.785 --> 11:28.219
- Good.
- Thanks.

11:48.974 --> 11:52.477
- I remember you.
Four kids, right?

11:52.479 --> 11:55.180
- Uh, yeah, yeah, that's me.
- Left them at home today?

11:55.182 --> 11:56.815
Table for one?
- Oh, no, no, no.

11:56.817 --> 11:59.184
No, actually, no,
I'm just here to, um...

11:59.186 --> 12:02.787
I-I gotta...Buy a couple
t-shirts for my kids.

12:02.789 --> 12:04.322
- Oh, great.
Come with me.

12:04.324 --> 12:06.925
- Thanks.

12:06.927 --> 12:09.327
- So I've got a child's small,
child's medium,

12:09.329 --> 12:11.830
And two adult smalls.

12:11.832 --> 12:15.200
That'll be an even 100.
- Dollars?

12:15.202 --> 12:20.338
- Yeah, sorry.
They are not cheap.

12:20.340 --> 12:24.342
- So, um, there was this girl
working here last time we came.

12:24.344 --> 12:28.379
- What's she look like?
- She had long brown hair.

12:28.381 --> 12:30.281
She--pretty.
- Alison?

12:30.283 --> 12:33.251
Yeah, she's not in right now.
- Okay.

12:33.253 --> 12:35.153
- Were you looking for her?
- No, no, no.

12:35.155 --> 12:39.257
She's just, um--I just wanted
to thank her for something.

12:39.259 --> 12:42.293
- Oh, I'll let her know
you stopped by.

12:42.295 --> 12:44.763
- Great, thanks, man.
- You got it.

12:48.501 --> 12:50.502
- Say, is there a library
in town?

13:43.088 --> 13:45.190
- Hi.
- Hi.

13:45.192 --> 13:47.091
- I heard you were looking
for me.

13:47.093 --> 13:49.894
- Yeah, I'm just, uh, I'm doing
some research for my book.

13:49.896 --> 13:54.432
- Oh, how about a tour
of the island?

13:54.434 --> 13:55.900
- Uh, actually, can we talk
for a second?

13:55.902 --> 13:57.402
- Mm-hmm.
- Thanks.

14:00.906 --> 14:06.444
So, uh...

14:06.446 --> 14:08.913
Look, how do I...

14:08.915 --> 14:14.452
I really like you.
But...

14:14.454 --> 14:18.089
- You're married.
- Right.

14:18.091 --> 14:20.625
- And you have a family.
- I do.

14:20.627 --> 14:23.061
- And you love them.
- Of course.

14:23.063 --> 14:26.331
- And you don't want to do
anything to jeopardize that.

14:26.333 --> 14:28.499
- You just made that
pretty easy for me.

14:28.501 --> 14:30.201
- I get it.
Of course I do.

14:30.203 --> 14:34.272
- [relieved sigh]
thank you.

14:34.274 --> 14:37.075
- Let's just be friends.
How does that sound?

14:37.077 --> 14:39.611
- That sounds great.
- Okay.

14:39.613 --> 14:41.079
So if you need help
with your book

14:41.081 --> 14:42.347
Or you need someone to talk to,

14:42.349 --> 14:45.016
Feel free to call me.

14:47.620 --> 14:50.054
But I promise,
I won't call you.

15:03.502 --> 15:07.171
- Hey, where ya headed, friend?

15:14.980 --> 15:18.249
- Hey, will.
- Hey, alison.

15:18.251 --> 15:20.919
This is my friend, noah.
He wants to buy some fish.

15:20.921 --> 15:22.287
- Hi.
- Great.

15:22.289 --> 15:24.322
We hit a round of porgies
last night, man.

15:24.324 --> 15:27.258
Does that interest you?
- Sure.

15:27.260 --> 15:28.660
Uh, well, I don't know
what they are exactly.

15:28.662 --> 15:30.261
But--
- they're good.

15:30.263 --> 15:32.997
And rare for these parts.
Buy 'em.

15:32.999 --> 15:35.133
- Okay.
- [chuckles]

15:35.135 --> 15:38.569
- Hey.
- Hey.

15:38.571 --> 15:42.040
- Mr. Solloway.
It's good to see you again.

15:42.042 --> 15:45.043
Scotty lockhart.
- Hi, scotty.

15:45.045 --> 15:48.413
- I see you discovered
the best kept secret in montauk.

15:48.415 --> 15:51.349
Will is like
the pied piper of fish.

15:51.351 --> 15:54.185
We keep him on something of
a monthly retainer at the ranch.

15:54.187 --> 15:58.222
Isn't that right, alison?
- That's right, scotty.

15:58.224 --> 16:00.625
- Well, it was good to
bump into you both.

16:00.627 --> 16:03.227
Don't let my sister-in-law
monopolize too much

16:03.229 --> 16:06.030
Of your time, mr. Solloway.
She's a talker.

16:06.032 --> 16:09.701
- [forced chuckle]

16:09.703 --> 16:12.303
- Oh, I invited myself over
for dinner tonight

16:12.305 --> 16:15.206
After the town hall.
So I hope that's okay.

16:15.208 --> 16:17.742
Cole says he's making ribs.
- Great.

16:17.744 --> 16:19.978
See you then.

16:25.651 --> 16:29.187
- You okay?
- Yeah.

16:29.189 --> 16:31.556
Fine.

16:33.058 --> 16:34.625
- You still want those fish,
man?

16:34.627 --> 16:36.995
- Oh, uh, uh...
No, thanks.

16:36.997 --> 16:38.663
Maybe next time.

16:43.068 --> 16:47.205
So there's a town hall tonight.
- Yep.

16:47.207 --> 16:50.341
- What's on the agenda?
- Mostly bullshit.

16:50.343 --> 16:52.377
- Can I come see it?

16:52.379 --> 16:55.546
I mean, is it open
to the public?

16:55.548 --> 16:57.615
- Yeah, I think so.

17:04.523 --> 17:07.759
- No, stop.
Stop, stop, stop, stop.

17:07.761 --> 17:10.762
Stop.
Didn't we talk about this?

17:10.764 --> 17:13.364
Come on.
Remember what I said.

17:13.366 --> 17:16.300
- You didn't say it, I did.
- Sure, whatever.

17:16.302 --> 17:18.703
Point is, I--

17:18.705 --> 17:21.539
- Okay.

17:21.541 --> 17:24.409
I get it.

17:24.411 --> 17:27.378
See you around.

17:38.524 --> 17:40.825
[silverware clinks]
- that was delicious, miranda.

17:40.827 --> 17:46.431
Thank you, I want to get
the recipe before we go.

17:46.433 --> 17:48.800
- Trevor?
- Yes, grandma?

17:48.802 --> 17:51.135
- Those peas are dead.
- I know.

17:51.137 --> 17:53.738
- Well, it's not necessary
to stab them with the cutlery.

17:53.740 --> 17:55.573
Why don't you try
using your knife

17:55.575 --> 17:58.409
To encourage them
upon the fork

17:58.411 --> 18:00.611
And then lift them all
gracefully to your mouth?

18:00.613 --> 18:02.313
- Mom?
- You can ignore her.

18:02.315 --> 18:03.681
It's okay.
Just finish your soup, honey.

18:03.683 --> 18:04.849
- So how'd it go today, whit?

18:04.851 --> 18:06.684
- Awful.
The kids are spoiled brats.

18:06.686 --> 18:08.686
- Really?
What's that like?

18:08.688 --> 18:10.354
- They don't do anything
I ask them to,

18:10.356 --> 18:12.156
And the mother
doesn't trust me anyway.

18:12.158 --> 18:14.592
She was hovering the whole time,
correcting everything I did.

18:14.594 --> 18:15.693
Oh, and the father's a lech.

18:15.695 --> 18:17.295
- A lech?
- Yeah.

18:17.297 --> 18:19.097
I caught him staring at my butt,
like, five times.

18:19.099 --> 18:20.364
- Okay, that's it.
She's not going back there.

18:20.366 --> 18:22.100
- Well, let's talk
about it later.

18:22.102 --> 18:23.468
- What's to talk about?
You heard what she said.

18:23.470 --> 18:25.336
- Yeah, I heard.
- And?

18:25.338 --> 18:28.106
- And I think whitney has
a tendency to exaggerate

18:28.108 --> 18:29.874
When she wants
to be persuasive.

18:29.876 --> 18:31.609
- Oh, great,
so you're calling me a liar now?

18:31.611 --> 18:34.178
- Sounds to me like the fellow
has taste.

18:34.180 --> 18:35.847
You can't fault him for that.
- Grandpa!

18:35.849 --> 18:37.615
- Yeah, dad,
stay out of this, please.

18:37.617 --> 18:39.183
- May I be excused?
- No.

18:39.185 --> 18:41.586
- May I be excused?
- Children, please.

18:41.588 --> 18:43.354
